TI  - Study on the screening of high-efficiency salt and alkali-tolerant microbial agents and their roles and mechanisms in enhancing saline-alkaline soil remediation
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Against the backdrop of limited global cultivable land reserves and rapidly increasing food demands, the improvement and utilization of saline-alkaline land carry substantial significance. Biological improvement not only enhances soil properties but also boosts biodiversity in saline-alkali ecosystems. However, the synergistic role of functional microbial agents in remediation and their impact on soil nutrient cycling mechanisms remain underexplored. In this study, a functional microbial agent Q3 was constructed by combining Bacillus oceanisediminis-Q1 and Acinetobacter indicus-Q2. Using biochar as a carrier, an efficient microbial formulation was prepared by immobilizing Q3. An in-depth study into its remediation effects on saline-alkali soil demonstrated that it significantly reduced soil salinity and alkalinity while effectively improving soil nutrient levels. Specifically, nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium contents increasing by 1.18, 2.6, and 1.8 times, respectively, compared to untreated soil. Structural Equation Modeling (SEM) revealed that Q3 enhanced soil nutrient cycling, enzyme activity, and microbial abundance. Further analysis via 16S rRNA sequencing revealed that the addition of the functional microbial agent led to increased expression levels of genes associated with carbon metabolism (rbcL, gltS), nitrogen cycling (nifH, amoA), and phosphorus metabolism (phoA, phoB, appA). Additionally, functional microorganisms such as Bacteroidetes, which play a critical role in carbon sequestration, and Proteobacteria, which are key drivers of the nitrification process, were significantly enriched. These microorganisms act as pivotal regulators of carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorus dynamics. This study demonstrated that the functional microbial agent influences the activity and community structure of indigenous microorganisms through its phosphorus-solubilizing and nitrogen-fixing capabilities. This effect is crucial for mitigating soil salinization, restoring soil nutrients, and rehabilitating saline-alkali land. The findings provide novel strategies and a robust theoretical basis for the ecological restoration of saline-alkali land and the sustainable development of agriculture.
