AB  - The reasons for nitrification inhibition in some soils are controversial. We studied the effect of Elaeagnus angustifolia leaf litter (a host plant able to fix atmospheric nitrogen via root-nodule symbiosis with an actinomycete of the genus Frankia) on the density and activity of nitrifying microorganisms present in degraded soils. Soils were incubated with and without leaf litter, and it was seen that increased denitrification, CO2-induced inhibition, or nitrite and ammonia fixation by organic matter did not decrease nitrification. Our results suggest allelopathic inhibition by leaf litter and indicate that the introduction of E. angustifolia could improve degraded soils because it stimulates nitrogen conservation.
